sentences: Timothy J. Kasher (born August 19, 1974) is a musician from Omaha, Nebraska, and is the frontman of indie rock groups Cursive and The Good Life, both of which are on the Omaha-based record label Saddle Creek Records.
Slowdown Virginia was formed in Omaha in 1993 by Kasher with Matt Maginn, Steve Pedersen, and Casey Caniglia after the dissolution of a previous band called The March Hares.
Slowdown Virginia was formed in Omaha in 1993 by Kasher with Matt Maginn, Steve Pedersen, and Casey Caniglia after the dissolution of a previous band called The March Hares.

The band was short lived, breaking up in 1995, but it inspired other bands to form in Omaha like The Faint and Bright Eyes, the formation of Saddle Creek Records out of Lumberjack Records, and the name of Omaha's indie music venue, Slowdown.
Kasher, Maginn, and Pedersen formed a new band, Cursive, in 1995, adding Clint Schnase to the band.
The bands released two albums, described as full of emotion and distortion, before disbanding in 1998 as Kasher moved to Portland, Oregon, after getting married.
Kasher's marriage and time away from Omaha did not last long; he returned within eighteen months of leaving Cursive and Omaha.
Cursive added cellist Gretta Cohn for the next several releases and the band, and Kasher's writing, found critical success with 2003's The Ugly Organ, a "gale force" of "personal indigence.
"Cohn departed Cursive in 2005, and the band continued on without a cellist.

Cursive has subsequently recorded and released three more studio albums, also concept albums - a style that Kasher began loosely with The Storms of Early Summer: Semantics of Song and developed full-blown with Domestica.
Cursive's last release was Vitriola in 2018.
He released Novena on a Nocturn under the name The Good Life on Better Looking Records in 2000, five months after Cursive's Domestica.
He released Novena on a Nocturn under the name The Good Life on Better Looking Records in 2000, five months after Cursive's Domestica.
2002's Black Out was also a mostly solo effort with friends assisting in the recording, and was released on Saddle Creek Records.
Kasher recruited Ryan Fox, Roger Lewis, and Stefanie Drootin-Senseney and released Album of the Year in 2004.
Kasher recruited Ryan Fox, Roger Lewis, and Stefanie Drootin-Senseney and released Album of the Year in 2004.

Despite his intention to make The Good Life a band in its own right, Kasher still retained most creative control over the band for much of Album of the Year and similarly for 2007's Help Wanted Nights, described by Pitchfork's Eric Harvey as "two consecutive concept albums dealing with boozers and their second homes.

Despite his intention to make The Good Life a band in its own right, Kasher still retained most creative control over the band for much of Album of the Year and similarly for 2007's Help Wanted Nights, described by Pitchfork's Eric Harvey as "two consecutive concept albums dealing with boozers and their second homes.
"The Good Life took a break after 2007.
Kasher released two albums with Cursive and two solo albums before reconvening The Good Life in late 2013.
The result was the rock-oriented Everybody's Coming Down, released in September 2015.
His first solo album, The Game of Monogamy, was released to mixed reviews on October 5, 2010, on Saddle Creek Records.
The follow-up EP, Bigamy: More Songs from the Monogamy Sessions, was released in August 2011.
Adult Film, Kasher's second solo album, was released on Saddle Creek Records in 2013.
Kasher's songwriting receives similar attention, particularly 2003's The Ugly Organ, which took an introspective meta view on the songwriting process itself.

Even prior to this, Kasher's writing for albums moved more and more towards a screenplay style of writing, to the point of the lyric sheet for I Am Gemini being described as one reviewer as "a full-blown libretto."
In 2007, Kasher moved from Omaha to Los Angeles, California.
In the fall of 2009, he relocated to Montana to focus more explicitly on his writing.
In the fall of 2009, he relocated to Montana to focus more explicitly on his writing.
He is currently again living in Los Angeles.
In 2015, Kasher married his long-term girlfriend Gwynedd, the digital managing editor at Los Angeles Magazine.
In 2017, feature film No Resolution—written and directed by Kasher starring Maura Kidwell and Layne Manzer—was released.
In an interview with The Reader (newspaper), Kasher said an earlier version premiered at the Omaha Film Festival a year prior in 2016.
